{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8e688a30-1e03-4d7a-aaa7-bdf399f7116f","content":"PID 12345 isn't running on this machine, so I can't inspect it directly. Here's how to diagnose and configure on **your** system:\n\n---\n\n### 1. Determine the runtime\n\n```bash\n# If coreclr/libclrjit are loaded → CoreCLR; if not → NativeAOT\ncat /proc/12345/maps | grep -iE 'coreclr|libclrjit'\n```\n\n- **Output with matches** → **CoreCLR**\n- **No matches** → likely **NativeAOT** (confirm with `file $(readlink /proc/12345/exe)` — NativeAOT binaries are statically linked and won't show \"interpreter\" in the ELF header)\n\n---\n\n### 2. Configure crash dumps\n\n#### For CoreCLR apps\n\nSet environment variables (e.g., in a systemd override or your launch script):\n\n```bash\n# Enable full crash dumps\nexport DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1\nexport DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType=4          # 4 = Full (Triage=1, Mini=2, Heap=3)\nexport DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName=/tmp/dumps/coredump.%p.%t\nmkdir -p /tmp/dumps\n```\n\n#### For NativeAOT apps\n\nNativeAOT doesn't use the CoreCLR dump infrastructure. Use the **kernel's core dump** mechanism instead:\n\n```bash\n# Set core dump pattern (requires root)\necho '/tmp/dumps/core.%e.%p.%t' | sudo tee /proc/sys/kernel/core_pattern\n\n# Remove core file size limit for the process\nulimit -c unlimited\n\nmkdir -p /tmp/dumps\n```\n\n#### For either runtime (systemd service)\n\nIf run via systemd, also add to your unit file:\n\n```ini\n[Service]\nLimitCORE=infinity\nEnvironment=DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1\nEnvironment=DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType=4\nEnvironment=DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName=/tmp/dumps/coredump.%p.%t\n```\n\n(The `DOTNET_*` vars are harmless no-ops for NativeAOT, so it's safe to set both.)\n\n---\n\n### Quick summary\n\n| | CoreCLR | NativeAOT |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Detection** | `libcoreclr.so` in `/proc/PID/maps` | No managed runtime libs loaded |\n| **Dump mechanism** | `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump` env vars | Kernel `core_pattern` + `ulimit -c` |\n| **Analysis tool** | `dotnet-dump analyze` / `lldb + SOS` | `lldb` / `gdb` (no SOS) |\n\nRun the detection command on your box and let me know which runtime it is — I can help fine-tune from there.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"de98b09b-6fa0-42fb-961a-5a5346db7068","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The process doesn't exist on this machine. That's expected — the user is asking about a process on their own system. Let me provide guidance on how to determine the runtime and configure dumps accordingly.","outputTokens":774,"requestId":"6017:2D2460:E02075:103F061:69EACB9C"},"id":"b28ed169-d97a-4efd-914c-59a7cc58c5fb","timestamp":"2026-04-24T01:47:25.660Z","parentId":"c9cbe541-d4c7-43ba-9107-ec4776ea8ef3"}
